# Specification Structure Rule

When creating or updating requirement specifications, follow the project specification system exactly.

## Primary location and format

- Business/domain requirement specifications live in `spec/requirements/`.
- Requirement documents in this area must use Markdown `.md`.
- Keep requirement docs prominent in `spec/requirements/` root.
- The overarching document is `spec/requirements/TPLK-Specification.md`.

## Mandatory hierarchy

Each specification document must use this hierarchy (as headings):

1. Topic
2. Use Case
3. Story
4. Item

Do not skip levels when adding detailed requirements.

## Mandatory label on every level

Every Topic, Use Case, Story, and Item must have exactly one status label.
Use plain Markdown status tokens in headings (for example `## Topic: ... [Spec]` and `##### Item: ... [Ready]`).
Do not use a dash before the status marker (write `Title [Ready]`, not `Title - [Ready]`).

Allowed labels only:

- `Spec` (ongoing specification)
- `Ready` (ready for implementation)
- `Impl` (being implemented)
- `QA` (QA test creation outstanding)
- `Done` (fully complete)

## German language quality

- If specification text is written in German, use proper umlauts (`ä`, `ö`, `ü`, `Ä`, `Ö`, `Ü`) and `ß` where linguistically correct.
- Avoid fallback spellings like `ae`, `oe`, `ue` in final German specification wording unless a technical key/name requires ASCII.

## Manual synchronization

- If the specification system/structure changes, update `doc/specification-manual.qmd` in the same change set.
- Keep wording concise and consistent with existing manuals.

